---
import BaseLayout from "../../layouts/BaseLayout.astro";
---

<BaseLayout
  title="Why Compiled, Not Interpreted - FraiseQL Philosophy"
  description="Understand why compile-time optimization beats runtime interpretation for GraphQL execution."
>
  <div style="padding: 2rem; max-width: 1280px; margin: 0 auto;">
    <h1>Why Compiled, Not Interpreted?</h1>
    <p style="font-size: 1.2rem; color: #666;">
      <strong>Move expensive work from runtime to compile time.</strong>
    </p>

    <section style="margin: 3rem 0;">
      <h2>The Cost of Runtime Interpretation</h2>
      <p>
        Every request, traditional GraphQL servers do expensive work:
      </p>
      <ul>
        <li>
          <strong>Parse GraphQL</strong> – Tokenize and build AST (0.5-1ms per request)
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong>Validate schema</strong> – Check query against schema, type system (0.2-0.5ms per request)
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong>Plan execution</strong> – Determine resolver order, dependencies (0.5-2ms per request)
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong>Optimize query</strong> – Merge resolvers, batch queries, identify N+1 (1-3ms per request)
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong>Execute resolvers</strong> – Call application code, data fetching, transformation (5-50ms per request)
        </li>
      </ul>
      <p style="margin-top: 1rem; color: #c41c3b;">
        <strong>Total overhead:</strong> 2-6ms of pure interpretation per request, before any actual work.
      </p>

      <p style="margin-top: 1rem; padding: 1rem; background: #fef2f2; border-radius: 4px;">
        <strong>At scale:</strong> 100,000 requests/sec = 200-600 seconds/sec wasted just parsing and planning.
      </p>
    </section>

    <section style="margin: 3rem 0;">
      <h2>What Happens at Compile Time Instead</h2>
      <p>
        In FraiseQL, expensive work moves to build time:
      </p>
      <pre><code>{`# Build time (once, during deployment)
$ fraiseql-cli compile schema.json fraiseql.toml
  ├─ Parse decorators from Python/TypeScript
  ├─ Validate schema structure
  ├─ Generate optimal SQL for each query
  ├─ Analyze query dependencies
  ├─ Optimize resolver chains
  ├─ Generate pre-compiled execution plan
  └─ Output: schema.compiled.json (pre-optimized)

# Runtime (per request, milliseconds)
$ Server loads schema.compiled.json (preloaded)
$ Client sends GraphQL query
$ Server looks up pre-compiled execution plan (O(1) hash lookup)
$ Server executes pre-generated SQL (just pass params to DB)
$ Server returns results`}</code></pre>

      <p style="margin-top: 1rem; color: #059669;">
        <strong>Result:</strong> Every request just executes pre-optimized SQL. No parsing, no planning, no interpretation.
      </p>
    </section>

    <section style="margin: 3rem 0;">
      <h2>Real-World Performance Comparison</h2>

      <p>
        <strong>Scenario: API serving 100,000 requests/sec</strong>
      </p>

      <table style="width: 100%; border-collapse: collapse; margin: 1rem 0;">
        <tr style="background: #f5f3ff;">
          <th style="padding: 1rem; text-align: left; border: 1px solid #e5e7eb;">Work Item</th>
          <th style="padding: 1rem; text-align: center; border: 1px solid #e5e7eb;">Interpreted (per req)</th>
          <th style="padding: 1rem; text-align: center; border: 1px solid #e5e7eb;">Compiled (per req)</th>
          <th style="padding: 1rem; text-align: center; border: 1px solid #e5e7eb;">Total/sec at 100K req/s</th>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td style="padding: 1rem; border: 1px solid #e5e7eb;">Parse GraphQL</td>
          <td style="padding: 1rem; text-align: center; border: 1px solid #e5e7eb;">0.5ms</td>
          <td style="padding: 1rem; text-align: center; border: 1px solid #e5e7eb;">—</td>
          <td style="padding: 1rem; text-align: center; border: 1px solid #e5e7eb;">50s wasted</td>
        </tr>
        <tr style="background: #fafafa;">
          <td style="padding: 1rem; border: 1px solid #e5e7eb;">Validate schema</td>
          <td style="padding: 1rem; text-align: center; border: 1px solid #e5e7eb;">0.3ms</td>
          <td style="padding: 1rem; text-align: center; border: 1px solid #e5e7eb;">—</td>
          <td style="padding: 1rem; text-align: center; border: 1px solid #e5e7eb;">30s wasted</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td style="padding: 1rem; border: 1px solid #e5e7eb;">Plan execution</td>
          <td style="padding: 1rem; text-align: center; border: 1px solid #e5e7eb;">1.0ms</td>
          <td style="padding: 1rem; text-align: center; border: 1px solid #e5e7eb;">—</td>
          <td style="padding: 1rem; text-align: center; border: 1px solid #e5e7eb;">100s wasted</td>
        </tr>
        <tr style="background: #fafafa;">
          <td style="padding: 1rem; border: 1px solid #e5e7eb;">Optimize query</td>
          <td style="padding: 1rem; text-align: center; border: 1px solid #e5e7eb;">1.5ms</td>
          <td style="padding: 1rem; text-align: center; border: 1px solid #e5e7eb;">—</td>
          <td style="padding: 1rem; text-align: center; border: 1px solid #e5e7eb;">150s wasted</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td style="padding: 1rem; border: 1px solid #e5e7eb;">Execute</td>
          <td style="padding: 1rem; text-align: center; border: 1px solid #e5e7eb;">1-3ms</td>
          <td style="padding: 1rem; text-align: center; border: 1px solid #e5e7eb;">0.05ms</td>
          <td style="padding: 1rem; text-align: center; border: 1px solid #e5e7eb;">5s vs 100ms</td>
        </tr>
        <tr style="background: #e8f5e9;">
          <td style="padding: 1rem; border: 1px solid #e5e7eb;"><strong>Total per request</strong></td>
          <td style="padding: 1rem; text-align: center; border: 1px solid #e5e7eb;"><strong>4.3-6.3ms</strong></td>
          <td style="padding: 1rem; text-align: center; border: 1px solid #e5e7eb;"><strong>0.05-0.1ms</strong></td>
          <td style="padding: 1rem; text-align: center; border: 1px solid #e5e7eb;"><strong>430-630s vs 5-10s</strong></td>
        </tr>
      </table>

      <p style="margin-top: 1rem; color: #059669;">
        <strong>Compilation saves 50-100 seconds of CPU per second of traffic.</strong> That's infrastructure you don't need to buy.
      </p>
    </section>

    <section style="margin: 3rem 0;">
      <h2>Key Benefits of Compilation</h2>

      <h3 style="margin-top: 2rem;">1. Performance (Obvious)</h3>
      <p>
        Pre-computed execution plans mean runtime is just parameter binding and execution. 10-50× faster for typical queries.
      </p>

      <h3 style="margin-top: 2rem;">2. Determinism (Powerful)</h3>
      <p>
        Query latency is deterministic because planning already happened:
      </p>
      <ul>
        <li>
          <strong>No surprise N+1 queries</strong> – Compiler catches these at build time, not runtime
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong>No unexpected performance cliffs</strong> – Query complexity is pre-analyzed
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong>SLA-friendly</strong> – P99 latency is predictable
        </li>
      </ul>

      <h3 style="margin-top: 2rem;">3. Error Catching (Earlier)</h3>
      <p>
        Errors caught at compile time instead of during request:
      </p>
      <ul>
        <li>
          <strong>Schema mismatches</strong> – Caught before deployment
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong>Invalid queries</strong> – Validated at build time
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong>Type errors</strong> – Caught before production
        </li>
      </ul>
      <p style="margin-top: 1rem; padding: 1rem; background: #f0fdf4; border-radius: 4px;">
        Result: No runtime "invalid query" errors. Clients know their queries are valid.
      </p>

      <h3 style="margin-top: 2rem;">4. Optimization Opportunities (Powerful)</h3>
      <p>
        Compiler can perform optimizations impossible at runtime:
      </p>
      <ul>
        <li>
          <strong>Query fusion</strong> – Merge multiple queries into one optimized statement
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong>Dead field elimination</strong> – Remove unused columns from SELECT
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong>Index recommendation</strong> – Suggest indices for slow queries before deployment
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong>Cardinality analysis</strong> – Estimate result set size, warn on large results
        </li>
      </ul>

      <h3 style="margin-top: 2rem;">5. Security (Built-in)</h3>
      <p>
        Compile-time analysis enables security checks that runtime interpretation misses:
      </p>
      <ul>
        <li>
          <strong>Constant-time field access</strong> – No timing attacks on authorization checks
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong>Query depth limits</strong> – Prevent DOS from deep nested queries (caught before execution)
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong>Cost estimation</strong> – Reject expensive queries before they run
        </li>
      </ul>
    </section>

    <section style="margin: 3rem 0;">
      <h2>The Compilation Pipeline</h2>

      <pre><code>{`# Phase 1: Schema Definition (Python/TypeScript)
@fraiseql.type
class User:
    id: int
    name: str
    posts: List[Post]

# Phase 2: Compilation (fraiseql-cli)
$ fraiseql compile schema.json fraiseql.toml
  1. Parse schema decorators
  2. Infer GraphQL types
  3. Generate query resolvers
  4. Optimize for single database
  5. Generate SQL templates
  6. Validate all combinations
  → schema.compiled.json (immutable, deployable)

# Phase 3: Runtime (fraiseql server)
$ fraiseql-server --config fraiseql.toml --schema schema.compiled.json
  1. Load pre-compiled schema (instant)
  2. Listen for GraphQL requests
  3. Look up query in compiled plan (O(1))
  4. Execute pre-generated SQL (just bind params)
  5. Return results

# Phase 4: Deployment (fraisier)
$ fraisier deploy --schema schema.compiled.json --blue-env prod-blue --green-env prod-green
  1. Test pre-compiled schema with health checks
  2. Deploy to blue environment
  3. Validate all queries work
  4. Switch traffic to blue (zero-downtime)`}</code></pre>

      <p style="margin-top: 1rem; color: #666;">
        <em>Each phase runs once. Runtime runs millions of times. Optimize where it matters.</em>
      </p>
    </section>

    <section style="margin: 3rem 0;">
      <h2>Tradeoff: Schema Rigidity</h2>
      <p>
        Compilation requires knowing your schema at build time. This means:
      </p>
      <ul>
        <li>
          <strong>Schema changes require recompilation</strong> – Can't add fields live
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong>Deployment needed for updates</strong> – Different from runtime interpretation
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong>Breaking changes caught early</strong> – CI/CD integration required
        </li>
      </ul>
      <p style="margin-top: 1rem; padding: 1rem; background: #fef2f2; border-radius: 4px;">
        <strong>This is a feature, not a bug.</strong> Catching breaking schema changes before production prevents customer-facing errors.
      </p>

      <h3 style="margin-top: 2rem;">When Runtime Interpretation is Better</h3>
      <p>
        Interpreted servers are better for:
      </p>
      <ul>
        <li>Rapid prototyping with frequent schema changes</li>
        <li>Admin panels where schema mirrors database exactly</li>
        <li>Multi-tenant systems where each tenant has different schema</li>
      </ul>
      <p style="margin-top: 1rem; color: #666;">
        <em>Use interpreted servers for these use cases. Use FraiseQL for production performance.</em>
      </p>
    </section>

    <section style="margin: 3rem 0;">
      <h2>Why Rust for the Compiler?</h2>
      <p>
        FraiseQL's compiler is written in Rust because:
      </p>
      <ul>
        <li>
          <strong>Performance</strong> – Compilation completes in milliseconds, not seconds
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong>Memory safety</strong> – No crashes parsing untrusted schema definitions
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong>Parallelism</strong> – Multi-threaded compilation for large schemas
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong>Shipping (fraiseql-cli)</strong> – Single binary, no runtime dependencies
        </li>
      </ul>

      <p style="margin-top: 1rem;">
        The runtime is also Rust because:
      </p>
      <ul>
        <li>
          <strong>No interpretation overhead</strong> – Rust is as fast as C
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong>Zero-cost abstractions</strong> – No garbage collection pauses during requests
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong>Memory efficiency</strong> – fraiseql-wire achieves 200K× memory improvement partly through Rust's memory model
        </li>
      </ul>
    </section>

    <section style="margin: 3rem 0;">
      <h2>Comparison: Interpreted vs Compiled</h2>

      <table style="width: 100%; border-collapse: collapse; margin: 1rem 0;">
        <tr style="background: #f5f3ff;">
          <th style="padding: 1rem; text-align: left; border: 1px solid #e5e7eb;">Dimension</th>
          <th style="padding: 1rem; text-align: center; border: 1px solid #e5e7eb;">Interpreted (e.g., Hasura)</th>
          <th style="padding: 1rem; text-align: center; border: 1px solid #e5e7eb;">Compiled (FraiseQL)</th>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td style="padding: 1rem; border: 1px solid #e5e7eb;"><strong>Query latency</strong></td>
          <td style="padding: 1rem; text-align: center; border: 1px solid #e5e7eb;">5-15ms (parsing + planning)</td>
          <td style="padding: 1rem; text-align: center; border: 1px solid #e5e7eb;">1-2ms (execution only)</td>
        </tr>
        <tr style="background: #fafafa;">
          <td style="padding: 1rem; border: 1px solid #e5e7eb;"><strong>Determinism</strong></td>
          <td style="padding: 1rem; text-align: center; border: 1px solid #e5e7eb;">Variable (P99 spikes possible)</td>
          <td style="padding: 1rem; text-align: center; border: 1px solid #e5e7eb;">Deterministic (P99 predictable)</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td style="padding: 1rem; border: 1px solid #e5e7eb;"><strong>Schema changes</strong></td>
          <td style="padding: 1rem; text-align: center; border: 1px solid #e5e7eb;">Live (no deployment needed)</td>
          <td style="padding: 1rem; text-align: center; border: 1px solid #e5e7eb;">Requires deployment</td>
        </tr>
        <tr style="background: #fafafa;">
          <td style="padding: 1rem; border: 1px solid #e5e7eb;"><strong>Error detection</strong></td>
          <td style="padding: 1rem; text-align: center; border: 1px solid #e5e7eb;">Runtime (customer impact)</td>
          <td style="padding: 1rem; text-align: center; border: 1px solid #e5e7eb;">Build-time (caught before deploy)</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td style="padding: 1rem; border: 1px solid #e5e7eb;"><strong>Infrastructure</strong></td>
          <td style="padding: 1rem; text-align: center; border: 1px solid #e5e7eb;">10-20 servers for 100K req/s</td>
          <td style="padding: 1rem; text-align: center; border: 1px solid #e5e7eb;">2-3 servers for 100K req/s</td>
        </tr>
      </table>
    </section>

    <section style="margin: 3rem 0;">
      <h2>Bottom Line</h2>
      <p>
        <strong>Move expensive work from runtime to compile time.</strong>
      </p>
      <ul>
        <li>✅ Parsing happens once, not 100,000 times per second</li>
        <li>✅ Query planning happens once, at deployment time</li>
        <li>✅ Optimization opportunities are 10× better with full schema context</li>
        <li>✅ Errors are caught before customers see them</li>
        <li>✅ Performance is deterministic and predictable</li>
        <li>✅ Infrastructure costs drop by 5-10×</li>
      </ul>
      <p style="margin-top: 2rem; padding: 1rem; background: #f0fdf4; border-left: 4px solid #059669; border-radius: 4px;">
        <strong>FraiseQL philosophy:</strong> Compilation is not a limitation. It's a superpower. Let the compiler do the hard work once so runtime is lightning-fast.
      </p>
    </section>

    <p style="margin-top: 3rem;">
      <a href="/why/cqrs-pattern">Next: Why CQRS Pattern →</a> | <a href="/">Home</a>
    </p>
  </div>
</BaseLayout>
